<p>"We make maps very purposefully for fun, combat sight lines, and performance," said Zampella. "So if you're able to control that destruction, [it can still be] different, because you might blow up this building one time, this building another, or nothing at all. That's where the flexibility comes in. But even when they are destroyed, the map is still full. We guarantee you that the map is still fun to play. So it's about making a map and then making multiple versions of that map that are all equally balanced and fun to play."</p><p>Zampella went on to argue that too much destruction would ruin the gameplay of the map, making it less fun. He reiterated that the developers are primarily concerned with ensuring the game is fun, above all else.</p><p>EA has already revealed <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/battlefield-6-maps/2900-6834/" data-ref-id="2900-6834">the nine Battlefield 6 maps</a> that will be available at launch. The game's <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-6-open-beta-release-date-time/1100-6533515/" data-ref-id="1100-6533515">open beta will begin on August 7</a> and <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-6-preorder-guide-ps5-xbox-physical-edition-retailer-bonuses/1100-6533616/" data-ref-id="1100-6533616">preorders are already live</a>. Battlefield 6 will launch on Xbox Series X|S, PlayStation 5, and PC on October 10.</p>
  
                        
    
        
        
  
